l\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-feedback\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-feedback\"></use></svg><span class=\"zDocsFeedbackButtonText\"> Feedback</span></span></div></div><div class=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><button aria-label=\"Show topic actions\" data-toggle=\"dropdown\" id=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-ellipsis-h\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-ellipsis-h\"></use></svg></button><div class=\"dropdown-menu zDocsDropdownMenu zDocsTopicActionsMobileDropdown dropdown-menu-right\"></div></div><div style=\"flex-basis: 100%; height: 0px;\"></div><ul class=\"zDocsTopicPageDetails\"><li class=\"zDocsTopicPageDate css-cinqea\">Last Updated<span class=\"css-cinqea\">Aug 14, 2024</span></li><li class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryDetailsItem\"><button class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryButton\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-topic-summary\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-topic-summary\"></use></svg>Summarize</button></li><li class=\"spacer\" role=\"presentation\"></li><div class=\"zDocsLabelWrapper\"><ul><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: Uniface\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=prod_uniface\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>Uniface</a></li><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: 10.4\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=uniface_10.4\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>10.4</a></li></ul></div></ul></header><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBody\" data-prismjs-copy=\"Copy\" data-prismjs-copy-error=\"Copy failed! Use Ctrl + C instead.\" data-prismjs-copy-success=\"Copied!\"><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBodyContent\" dir=\"ltr\"><div id=\"zDocsAiSummaryContaineruniface_104thj1665702664733.html\"></div><div><article class=\"hascomments\" data-page=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/thj1665702664733.html\" id=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/thj1665702664733.html\"><main role=\"main\"><article aria-labelledby=\"ariaid-title1\" class=\"dita\" id=\"thj1665702664733\" role=\"article\">\n<h1 class=\"title topictitle1\" id=\"ariaid-title1\">\n      Data Retrieval on SEQ\n </h1>\n<div class=\"body conbody\" id=\"thj1665702664733__data_retrieval_on_seq_171357\"><p class=\"shortdesc\">When opening sequential files, Uniface attempts to establish both read and write\n      access. If this fails, Uniface opens them with read-only access. Users can read data, but any\n      attempt to update the data causes the appropriate warning or error message to be\n      returned.</p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"thj1665702664733__p_d58298e1_d58299e1_d58300e1\">Because SEQ is based on system-dependent I/O calls, it is not possible for the connector to distinguish between violation of read-only access and any other I/O error. If users have read-only access and they try to write to a sequential file, inappropriate messages can result, including <code class=\"ph codeph\">bad file number</code>, or <code class=\"ph codeph\">occurrence no longer exists</code>. Remember that there is no locking available at any time; sequential files should be used by single users only. You should take these limitations into account when using the SEQ connector in a production environment.</p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"thj1665702664733__p_d58301e1_d58302e1_d58303e1\">The retrieveSequential trigger is not supported.</p>\n</div>\n</article></main></article>\n</div></div><div class=\"contentPlaceholder\" style=\"height: 500px;\"><div class=\"contentContainer zDocsSideBoxes\"><div><h5 aria-level=\"5\" class=\"css-g931ng\">Related Links</h5><ul><li><a class=\"css-ettsdk\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/tut1665702663138.html\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-related-link\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-related-link\"></use></svg>Data Retrieval</a><p>Every DBMS connector recognizes the same set of connector I/O requests. When retrieving data from the database, Uniface selects the required data with the Select connector request, and fetches it into the component with the Fetch connector request. Uniface uses the Select request to create a partially built hitlist called a stepped hitlist.</p></li><li><a class=\"css-ettsdk\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/mnp1719929686696.html\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-related-link\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-related-link\"></use></svg>Data Retrieval Support</a><p>In response to read and selectdb ProcScript instructions, Uniface issues connector requests to select data into a hitlist and fetch it into the calling component. Special considerations and restrictions may apply for some databases.</p></li></ul></div></div></div></div><div class=\"bottomFeedback\"><div aria-labelledby=\"bottomFeedbackText\" class=\"bottomFeedbackContent\" role=\"group\"><span class=\"bottomFeedbackText\" id=\"bottomFeedbackText\">Was this topic helpful?</span><div class=\"bottomFeedbackButtonGroup\"><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2532353\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-up\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-up\"></use></svg><span>Like</span></a><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2532353\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-down\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-down\"></use></svg><span>Dislike</span></a></div></div></div><div style=\"position: fixed; bottom: 170px; right: 70px; cursor: pointer; transition-duration: 0.2s; transition-timing-function: linear; transition-delay: 0s; z-index: 3; opacity: 0; visibility: hidden; transition-property: opacity, visibility;\"><button aria-label=\"Scroll to top\" class=\"zDocsScrollTopBtn\" data-tooltip-content=\"Scroll to top\" data-tooltip-id=\"zDocsBackToTopToolTip\" id=\"zDocsScrollToTop\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-next\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-next\"></use></svg></button></div></body></html>", "text": "Data Retrieval on SEQ Add to My Topics Add selected topic and subtopics Add Topic & Subtopics with topic head Add entire publication Watch Download PDF Save selected topic Save selected topic and subtopics Save entire publication Share Email Link Copy Link Feedback Last Updated Aug 14, 2024 Summarize Uniface 10.4 Data Retrieval on SEQ When opening sequential files, Uniface attempts to establish both read and write access. If this fails, Uniface opens them with read-only access. Users can read data, but any attempt to update the data causes the appropriate warning or error message to be returned. Because SEQ is based on system-dependent I/O calls, it is not possible for the connector to distinguish between violation of read-only access and any other I/O error. If users have read-only access and they try to write to a sequential file, inappropriate messages can result, including bad file number , or occurrence no longer exists . Remember that there is no locking available at any time; sequential files should be used by single users only. You should take these limitations into account when using the SEQ connector in a production environment. The retrieveSequential trigger is not supported. Related Links Data Retrieval Every DBMS connector recognizes the same set of connector I/O requests. When retrieving data from the database, Uniface selects the required data with the Select connector request, and fetches it into the component with the Fetch connector request. Uniface uses the Select request to create a partially built hitlist called a stepped hitlist. Data Retrieval Support In response to read and selectdb ProcScript instructions, Uniface issues connector requests to select data into a hitlist and fetch it into the calling component. Special considerations and restrictions may apply for some databases. Was this topic helpful? Like Dislike"}